SIMPLE: hatchel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hatchel
<hw>Hatch"el</hw> <pr>(-⟦ecr⟧l; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hechele</ets>, <ets>hekele</ets>; akin to D. <ets>hekel</ets>, G.
<ets>hechel</ets>, Dan. <ets>hegle</ets>, Sw. <ets>h⟦aum⟧kla</ets>, and
prob. to E. <ets>hook</ets>. See <er>Hook</er>, and cf. <er>Hackle</er>,
<er>Heckle</er>.]</ety> <def>An instrument with long iron teeth set in a
board, for cleansing flax or hemp from the tow, hards, or coarse part; a
kind of large comb; -- called also <altname>hackle</altname> and
<altname>heckle</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatchel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hatchel
<hw>Hatch"el</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hatcheled</conjf> or <conjf>Hatchelled</conjf>
<pr>(-⟦ecr⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hatcheling</conjf> or <conjf>Hatchelling</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[OE. <ets>hechelen</ets>, <ets>hekelen</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>hekelen</ets>, G. <ets>hecheln</ets>, Dan. <ets>hegle</ets>, Sw.
<ets>h⟦aum⟧kla</ets>. See <er>Hatchel</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw through the teeth of a hatchel, as flax or
hemp, so as to separate the coarse and refuse parts from the fine,
fibrous parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To tease; to worry; to torment.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hatcheler</ent>⟦br⟧
